                <td rowspan="5" colspan="3" valign="top"> 
                  <div align="left"> 
                    <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4">
                       <tr> 
                        <td height="63"><img src="../global/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="1"> 
                           <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td bgcolor="#000000" height="8" width="100%" colspan="3"><span class="header">Gaining Every Advantage</span></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor="#333399" height="2" width="41%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="1%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="58%" bgcolor="#FF9C00"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td></tr></table><TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/4.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=43"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=43"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=5763">Joshua "Capt Barclay" Carey</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Description</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>This article is a must-read for all those willing to win at STCCG at any costs, the faint of heart should go no furthur (faint of heart does include fun players)</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Article</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>1) Always listen carefully-<br>
To the TDs instructions, pairings, opponent&#146;s actions, etc. The TD may give out information you need (especially in special formats such as Warp Speed or Mirror Mirror Tournaments), which could hinder your ability to win. Always listen to pairings. Although unlikely, if 4 people mishear the pairings, a great fiasco could happen when scores are reported. Always listen to your opponent. This can often be very difficult. Some players may have a speech impediment, or, if both players have different native languages, if can be difficult. If this happens, ask to have cards shown to you when they are played. Remember, the rules states you are allowed to look at any card when its reported to a Facility, meaning, don&#146;t just glance at it across the table, hold the card as close to you as needed to understand its text.<br>
<br>
2) Ask questions-<br>
If at any time during a tournament you don&#146;t know what&#146;s happening, ask questions. &quot;What did you just do?&quot; Is a perfectly good question to ask an opponent who just used an unfamiliar action. If for any reason you&#146;re unsure of a ruling, ask the TD. While this may cause lengthy delays, finding out that your opponent committed an illegal action after you&#146;ve just lost 100-0 does you no good.<br>
<br>
3) Size up your opponent-<br>
Is there any way through the personality of your opponent you can gain an advantage? It&#146;s likely a player at 8(+400) going into the final round is a bit @#$%y at least, maybe not much, but likely. Therefore, some of your earlier actions may be ones to boost his/her confidence, the more confident someone is, the more likely they are to make mistakes. A player who is 2(-300) going into the final round (with a bye) probably has a weak deck, but never count them out. In a 9 person, 5 round event, you could have a 3rd place deck, and still be playing this person. Look for weaknesses not only in their strategy, but in themselves. If they&#146;re sick of playing already, make some aggressive moves towards the beginning of the game, to lower their confidence, and drive to an easy victory.<br>
<br>
4) Remember Rule of Acquisition 85<br>
Never let the competition know what you&#146;re thinking. If your opponent sees your strategy by your missions, they&#146;ll be able to beat you quickly. If you have 6 Patrol Neutral Zones as your missions, you&#146;re opponent will self seed a Balancing Act, or put it at the mission they&#146;re going to steal. They&#146;ll follow with a first turn download of Wake of the Borg, and shut down your deck immediately. However, a 3 planet, 3 space scheme with each mission having icons for 2 affiliations consistently, with no, or both of the, Homeworlds, may be very confusing. Even during the game you&#146;ll want to avoid tipping your opponent off. Saying &quot;Interrupt&quot; before their first action, but realizing you can&#146;t won&#146;t help, as their first action may then change to beam all their people form the ship to the planet (avoiding Temporal Rift, RBM ,Time Travel Pod, etc.). Don&#146;t use Artifacts stored in your hand, as your opponent knows at least a turn in advance what you plan to do. Most of all never tell them what your deck is doing before thgame starts. An even better strategy might be to tell them a false strategy before the game starts, which seems appropriate to your missions, to throw them off.<br>
<br>
5) Take advantage of everything<br>
If your opponent makes one mistake pounce on it immediately. Don&#146;t hesitate, as your opportunity might disappear. Also, never be afraid to take the advantage from a new player. Once I was told by a new player she would not steal my mission. She was playing a geology Deck based on several Geological Surveys. I immediately stole one, despite her not willing to steal mine. Referring to Rule 3, know when someone will believe you. After a player hit an Alien Parasites against me, I told them to beam their entire crew down to the next mission they were attempting. Naturally, he then it The Higher... The Fewer. While I still lost the latter game, it did hinder his progress.<br>
<br>
Quite a few of these rules are fundamentary, just as many are hard core, require a lot of thinking and planning, and you may want to hold off on using them until you get to a championship event.<br>
<br>
 </span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=43"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=43"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="/stccg/global/images/back.gif" border="0" ></a></TD><TD><a href="articleprint.php3?article=43" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="/stccg/global/images/print.gif" border="0"></a></TD></TR></TABLE>
